---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const title = 'How CrossDrop Works – Peer-to-Peer WebRTC File Transfer Explained';
const description =
  'How CrossDrop transfers files between Android, iPhone, Windows, and Mac without a server: QR pairing, WebRTC data channels, chunked streaming, and mandatory encryption — explained step by step.';

const jsonLd = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'CrossDrop', item: 'https://crossdrop.app/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'How it works', item: 'https://crossdrop.app/how-it-works' },
    ],
  },
];
---

<Base {title} {description} {jsonLd}>
  <article class="wrap article">
    <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
    <h1>Your files go device-to-device. Here's exactly what that means.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Most "send a file to another phone" tools quietly upload your file to a
      server, then download it again on the other side — slow, and your data
      sits on someone else's machine. CrossDrop takes a different route: the
      two devices talk to each other directly.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Pairing: a room code and a QR code</h2>
    <p>
      When you open CrossDrop, it asks our tiny pairing server for a fresh
      room — a short, human-readable code like
      <code class="mono">swift-otter-42</code> — and renders it as a QR code.
      The second device joins by scanning the code or typing it in. Rooms
      hold exactly two devices, are single-use, and expire after ten minutes
      if nobody joins.
    </p>

    <h2>2. The handshake: WebRTC signaling</h2>
    <p>
      Once both devices are in the room, they exchange a small set of
      connection details through the pairing server: a session description
      (what each browser can do) and ICE candidates (the network addresses
      each device can be reached at). This is the only job the server has.
      It never sees file names, file sizes, or file contents — only the
      handshake, which it forgets the moment pairing completes.
    </p>

    <h2>3. The direct connection</h2>
    <p>
      With addresses exchanged, the browsers open a direct
      <strong>WebRTC data channel</strong> between the two devices. On the
      same Wi-Fi network, this connection usually forms over the local
      network itself — your files never leave your router. That's why
      transfers run at local Wi-Fi speed instead of being throttled by your
      internet upload speed.
    </p>
    <p>
      A public STUN server helps devices discover their addresses when they
      sit behind different routers. On networks that block direct
      connections entirely (some corporate and hotel networks), a TURN relay
      can carry the encrypted stream as a fallback.
    </p>

    <h2>4. The transfer: chunked, streamed, and full quality</h2>
    <p>
      Files are sliced into small chunks (around 64 KB) and streamed over
      the data channel in order, with backpressure handling so the pipe
      stays full without overwhelming either device. The receiver reassembles
      the chunks into an exact byte-for-byte copy — no recompression, no
      resizing, no format conversion. For very large files, supporting
      browsers can stream chunks straight to disk as they arrive.
    </p>

    <h2>5. Encryption isn't a feature — it's the protocol</h2>
    <p>
      Every WebRTC connection is encrypted in transit with DTLS. It is
      mandatory in the standard: an unencrypted WebRTC data channel simply
      cannot exist. Combined with the fact that files never touch a server,
      that means nobody in the middle — including us — can read what you
      send.
    </p>

    <h2>Known limitation: isolated Wi-Fi networks</h2>
    <p>
      Some routers enable <em>AP/client isolation</em>, which blocks devices
      on the same Wi-Fi from talking to each other (common on guest and
      hotel networks). If pairing fails there, a phone hotspot with both
      devices connected to it works reliably.
    </p>

    <p class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/#transfer">Try it now — send a file</a>
      <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/vs-airdrop">Compare with AirDrop</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .article { max-width: 44rem; padding-block: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4.5rem); }
  .lede { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .article h2 { margin-top: 2.25rem; }
  code { background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--mesh); border-radius: 6px; padding: 0.1em 0.4em; font-size: 0.9em; }
  .cta-row { display: flex; gap: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2.5rem; }
</style>
